  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      In children with OSA (Obstructive sleep apnea) adenotonsillectomy is regarded as the first
      choice of treatment. Studies in recent years have shown that the procedure does not always
      have the expected effect. Children with OSA are at greater risk for complications from the
      procedure.

      There is disagreement regarding the need for sleep studies in children prior to surgery in
      order to verify an OSA diagnosis. Today less than 10% of these children have polysomnography
      (PSG).

      The main purpose of this study is to describe the prevalence of OSA among children referred
      for adenotonsillectomy.

      The investigators will also examine these children prior to and six months after surgery to
      assess their sleep pattern and quality of life.

      The project outcome aims to improve the precision and quality of diagnosis and the short and
      long term effects of treatment of children with OSA.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
